 incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(1177,112,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(1178,112,'second_paragraph','The companies that build the algorithms behind policing technologies take for granted existing approaches to policing and punishment, approaches that communities are actively contesting. What should the police’s role be? What is the real meaning of public safety? Are there better ways to prevent and redress harm? Those are questions that must always be part of ongoing democratic deliberation about justice. But policing algorithms codify assumptions about justice, the reby preserving the status quo.\r\n\r\nMost of us are unaware of the ways that algorithmic tools, trained on information gathered through continuous mass surveillance, are influencing legal system actors who have enormous power over our lives. This project’s goal is to illuminate that fact and to begin the process of making an opaque and disorienting system legible.'),(1179,112,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(1180,112,'download_title',''),(1181,112,'_download_title','field_62b94d9d21dc3'),(1182,112,'download_bold_part_paragraph','This website is accompanied by an essay expanding on the harms of algorithms in policing and punishment and an appendix containing an '),(1183,112,'_download_bold_part_paragraph','field_62b94da721dc4'),(1184,112,'download_paragraph',' annotated bibliography of some of the most important scholarship on the use of algorithms in the criminal legal system.'),(1185,112,'_download_paragraph','field_62b94e6921dc5'),(1186,112,'acknowledgements_bold_part_paragraph','This project would not be possible without the tireless research and advocacy of our friends and allies who also seek a more just and equitable American criminal legal system.'),(1187,112,'_acknowledgements_bold_part_paragraph','field_62b94fd7582da'),(1188,112,'acknowledgements_paragraph','This includes lawyers, advocates, journalists, scholars and activists, as well a s everyone e