itle','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(1891,42,'app_file',''),(1892,42,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(1893,216,'title','Pre-trial jail'),(1894,216,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(1895,216,'text_in_left_part','You are told that you’ve been arrested for shoplifting, but are not given any information about how you were how you were identified, or the fact that you were being monitored as an “at-risk individual.” While held in jail, you are given maximum supervision.'),(1896,216,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(1897,216,'title_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition'),(1898,216,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(1899,216,'description_for_pop-up_1','Unbeknownst to you, the police officer had previously run the photo of a suspect in a shoplifting case through a face recognition system. You were returned as a match for the suspect, which formed the basis of the warrant for your arrest.'),(1900,216,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(1901,216,'subtitle_1','Basics'),(1902,216,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(1903,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition technology, (often called “facial” recognition), is an algorithmic biometric tool that which compares two face images to determine the likelihood they are a match. Law enforcement purportedly uses face recognition to produce leads when trying to identify people in photos or video footage. There are generally two types of face recognition: one-to-one matching, which compares two photos to one another to verify they’re the same person; and one-to-many matching, which compares one photo to a large database in order to identify someone. In the latter, officers upload a “probe” photo of a face in question, and an algorithm analyzes its features, compares it to a database of face photos, and then issues a numerical score reflecting the similarity of the “probe” photo face to other faces in the database. \r\n\r\nWhen analyzing a photo, the algorithm first detects the presence of a face. Then, it “normalizes” the image, scaling and rotating so it’s in a standard position for comparison. Next, it extracts facial features like eyes and nose from the image. Finally, it compares these features to those in another photo, assigning a score based on how similar they are. Face recognition refers to this specific process, as distinct from other face analysis tools that purport to classify people’s faces by factors like gender or age.\r\n\r\nFor more on the basics of face recognition technology, see:'),(1904,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(1905,216,'title_for_pop-up_2','Crime forecasting'),(1906,216,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(1907,216,'description_for_pop-up_2','You were designated as an “at-risk” individual by a crime forecasting algorithm, not necessarily as a perpetrator of crime, but potentially as a victim. As such, you were subject to heightened monitoring by law enforcement.'),(1908,216,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(1909,216,'subtitle_2','Basics'),(1910,216,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(1911,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','“Crime forecasting” refers to two separate but related processes: predictive policing and data-driven prosecution. Both processes use historical crime data to make predictions about future crime, using these predictions to inform who is policed and prosecuted. Based on existing “hot spot” theories of policing, crime forecasting assumes there are particular areas and individuals who are more “at-risk” for criminal activity. Automated tools analyze data such as where past crimes occurred and features of the local environment to determine if a location is “at-risk,” or if an individual is “likely” to commit or be the victim of a crime. Law enforcement sees these tools as more efficient and less biased than humans, capable of making quick decisions while also cutting costs. \r\n\r\n'),(1912,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(1913,216,'title_for_pop-up_3','Case management, planning, and supervision (jail)'),(1914,216,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(1915,216,'description_for_pop-up_3','A RAT tool has considered you to be at a high risk for violence, so you are given maximum security while held in jail awaiting trial.'),(1916,216,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(1917,216,'subtitle_3','RAT: jail case management, planning, and supervision'),(1918,216,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(1919,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_3','In jails, RATs are used to supplement case management, a process intended to reduce risk by ensuring individuals have access to needed resources. Case management refers to the process in which officials evaluate incarcerated peoples’ needs and risks, and connect them to appropriate services and programs. Intended to provide continuity of care between incarceration and the community, case management considers factors related to physical and mental health, substance abuse, education, housing, and employment.\r\n\r\nIn this context RATs serve to automate the evaluation and resource recommendation functions. They’re used to funnel scarce resources—attention and programming from case managers—towards the supposedly highest risk individuals. These tools are not only diagnostic but distributive as well; they are meant to provide case managers with recommendations about how to best reduce individuals’ risks based on their evaluated needs.'),(1920,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(1921,216,'lilst_items_item_1','Clare Garvie, Alvaro Bedoya, Jonathan Frankle, The Perpetual Line-Up: Unregulated Police Face Recognition in America, https://www.perpetuallineup.org/ '),(1922,216,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(1923,216,'lilst_items_item_2','Stan Z. Li, Anil K. Jain, “The Handbook of Face Recognition,” Second Edition, https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235709405_Handbook_of_Face_Recognition_the_second_edition'),(1924,216,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_6