0,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Once at trial, RATs are used to inform judges’ sentencing determinations. RATs purporting to predict the risk of an individual committing another crime in the future—their “dangerousness”—guide judges when deciding how and for how long to punish those convicted. In contrast to pretrial RATs, which are used to make binary decisions (for example, if someone is labeled as a flight risk or likely to commit a crime before trial, they are detained; if not, they are released), sentencing RATs are used to make even more complex, multi-faceted decisions. Judges must determine what kind of punishment or remedy is warranted, and, if incarcerated, the length of time.'),(2204,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2205,220,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(2206,220,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2207,220,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(2208,220,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2209,220,'subtitle_2',''),(2210,220,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2211,220,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(2212,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2213,220,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2214,220,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2215,220,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2216,220,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2217,220,'subtitle_3',''),(2218,220,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2219,220,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2220,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2221,220,'lilst_items_item_1',''),(2222,220,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2223,220,'lilst_items_item_2',''),(2224,220,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2225,220,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(2226,220,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2227,220,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2228,220,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2229,220,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2230,220,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2231,220,'lilst_items',''),(2232,220,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97