re misconduct; specifically, the chance an individual will skip bail, commit another crime, or be rearrested. They are also used to anticipate challenges incarcerated people will have during transitions into and out of institutionalization.\r\n\r\nWith “risk” in mind, criminal legal system officials make decisions about peoples’ liberty, supervision, and criminogenic needs. There are six main stages at which RATs are employed: pretrial, jail, prison, release, parole, and probation. Most notably, RATs are used for setting bail, case management in jails, sentencing, case management in prisons, informing discretionary release/parole, case management during parole, and determining probation. However, they can theoretically be used at any point during an individual’s interaction with the criminal legal system.\r\n\r\n<strong>For more on the basics of risk assessment tools, see:</strong>'),(2856,248,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2857,248,'title_for_pop-up_2','Bail (pretrial)'),(2858,248,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2859,248,'description_for_pop-up_2','A RAT tool has considered you a flight risk, and thus you have been denied bail.'),(2860,248,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2861,248,'subtitle_2','Risk assessment tools (RATs)'),(2862,248,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2863,248,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','A defendant often has their first encounter with an RAT before trial when their bail is being set. Here, RATs are used in one of two ways: to gauge the likelihood of an individual’s failure to appear (FTA) at their trial, or to assess their likelihood of committing another crime before trial. Historically, bail was used exclusively as a means to ensure court appearances and discourage flight. However, due to a number of political shifts, the concept of an individual’s “dangerousness” to the community became a major factor in bail determination. RATs, when used to set bail, now score people based on their FTA likelihood and risk of committing a crime after pretrial release.\r\n\r\nInitially, some critics of mass incarceration supported this application of RATs as a way to decrease pretrial detention rates and eliminate the disadvantage poor people face with cash bail. But these tools led to only small increases in pretrial release, and, in fact, increased FTAs and pretrial crime rates. Moreover, they yet again exhibit the limitations of data-driven technologies: because RATs are trained on specific data, they fail to reflect the true complex realities of the criminal legal system. Across place and time, RATs apply a one-size-fits-all approach to different contexts not necessarily compatible with the originally collected data. For example, RATs are often trained on older data; but if a jurisdiction has since instituted pretrial reforms, the RAT will reflect outdated practices rather than current ones. If a new diversion program is introduced to decrease pretrial detention and recidivism, the RAT does not take this into account, hiding any potential effects the reform has and reinforcing historical trends.'),(2864,248,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2865,248,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2866,248,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2867,248,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2868,248,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2869,248,'subtitle_3',''),(2870,248,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2871,248,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2872,248,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2873,248,'lilst_items_item_1','“Public Safety Risk Assessment Clearinghouse,” Bureau of Justice Assistance, US Department of Justice, https://psrac.bja.ojp.gov/ '),(2874,248,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2875,248,'lilst_items_item_2','“Use of Valid Actuarial Assessments of Risks and Needs,” National Parole Resource Center, https://nationalparoleresourcecenter.org/action-guide-use-of-valid-actuarial-assessments-of-risks-and-needs/selecting-a